<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Imro gives boost to new watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Another change in the structure for regulating retail financial services
announced yesterday should give further impetus to the setting up of the
Personal Investment Authority, the new watchdog to protect the private
investor.
Imro, the self-regulatory organisation for the investment management
industry, said it was reducing its scope to cut down the overlap between
organisations that could be regulated by it instead of by the PIA. It
estimates that about 40 of its 1100-member firms fall into this category.
The arrangements remove the option of staying with the existing regulator
from some members of Imro.
Instead, they will have to choose between joining the new regulator - the
more likely course - or insisting on exercising their right to be regulated
directly by the Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
