<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Council shake-up in Surrey urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Surrey County Council should be abolished and replaced by all-purpose
unitary authorities, The Local Government Commission recommended yesterday.
The commission proposed a similar fate for Hereford and Worcester County
Council, and in its report on Nottinghamshire it recommended that Nottingham
become self-governing.
The commission's decision to favour retention of the status quo of two-tier
counties and districts as an option in all three counties suggested further
conflict with the government's desire for unitary authorities.
The recommendations were:
Surrey: A choice is offered between a new five-unitary structure, with
boundaries almost totally different from those of the present districts, or
keeping the status quo.
The preferred option is to create five unitaries, although the commission
makes pessimistic forecasts on costs. Set-up costs would be between Pounds
40m and Pounds 44m and annual savings would be between Pounds 5m and Pounds
1m. It could take 44 years to recoup reorganisation costs.
The five unitaries would be: Epsom Downs, based on Epsom and Ewell District
Council, plus Esher, Leatherhead and Banstead; North Surrey, based on
Spelthorne borough, plus Weybridge; North West Surrey, a merged Surrey
Heath, Runnymede and Woking boroughs; South East Surrey, based on Tandridge
district, plus southern parts of Mole Valley and Reigate and Banstead
boroughs; South West Surrey, based on a merger of Guildford and Waverley.
Hereford and Worcester: Herefordshire to re-appear on the local government
map after an absence of 20 years. The commission, reflecting the view of all
local authorities in Hereford and Worcester, recommends that Herefordshire
be a unitary authority.
Worcestershire should be split into two unitary authorities, north and
south. Local authorities are divided on this. The county is prepared to
accept two unitary authorities if two tiers of government were not kept,
while the districts want Worcestershire split into five unitary authorities.
In addition to its preferred option, the commission will consult on plans
for a single Worcestershire unitary council or for the present arrangements
 -a county council, five district councils and one new district council. The
commission estimates that if Hereford and Worcester were split into three,
transitional costs would be up to Pounds 26m, with annual savings of Pounds
4m to Pounds 7m.
Nottinghamshire: The city of Nottingham should have its own unitary
authority but the rest of Nottinghamshire should retain two tiers of local
government.
Mr David Thomas, commissioner responsible for the county, said: 'We have
found the Notts review very difficult.' The eight local authorities and the
county council all held to stances designed to protect their position, and
could not agree on a list of options.
Nor has the commission been able to find a regular pulse of public opinion.
Mr Thomas said: 'The people seeking change are about the same number as
those wanting the status quo.'
Although the commission has not found a satisfactory case for change outside
Nottingham, it is offering options of seven unitary authorities or four
unitary authorities.
</TEXT>
<XX>
