<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Training charity to be relaunched: GrandMet will provide
Pounds 50,000 a year for ethnic campaign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fullemploy, the charity which catered for the training of ethnic minorities
before it collapsed under debts three years ago, is to be relaunched today.
The charity was founded 20 years ago to develop training centres in the
inner cities as part of an attempt to address higher than average
unemployment among ethnic minorities. It had government funding of Pounds 1m
a year at its peak and backing from the corporate sector.
Fullemploy embarked on an ambitious expansion programme through its trading
arm. By the end of the 1980s it was involved in a number of activities
including publishing and campaigning.
It was hit by the resignations of two chief executives in quick succession
and government cuts in funding for employment training schemes. Fullemploy
went into liquidation in early 1991.
Today's relaunch comes after two years of work by GrandMet Trust, a
charitable organisation funded by Grand Metropolitan, the food and drinks
company, which bought the assets from the liquidators after an approach by
the charity's former management.
GrandMet Trust has merged Fullemploy's training centres with its own,
combined some of its other functions with the Urban Trust, and absorbed the
accounting and personnel functions. The rescue package has cost GrandMet
Trust about Pounds 150,000, with another Pounds 120,000 coming from Home
Office grants.
Mr Geoffrey Bush, group community relations director at GrandMet, said
Fullemploy had been over-extended.
What will emerge is a consultancy service called Project Fullemploy, with a
staff of six, housed in the Truman Brewery, in the east end of London, which
is home to several GrandMet charities.
Its emphasis will be on helping to develop specialist training and
employment-creating programmes for organisations with special attention to
equal opportunities.
Another important role will be to help foster a business ethos in the black
community.
Mr Joel O'Loughlin, director of Project Fullemploy said: 'The reasons
Fullemploy started have not gone away. Black unemployment remains higher
than ever but we are taking a different route to addressing the same
problem.'
GrandMet Trust is to fund the organisation through a Pounds 50,000 annual
grant for the next three years and provide free office space and accountancy
support. British Gas, Shell and Morgan Grenfell are making donations.
The government is to provide support this year.
</TEXT>
