<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / OECD criticises record of Tecs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The performance of training and enterprise councils, the employer-led bodies
charged with transforming vocational training in England and Wales, has
'fallen short of initial expectations', says a report from the Organisation
of Economic Co-operation and Development, David Goodhart writes.
The judgment is contained in an unpublished note on the UK labour market
produced for last month's OECD jobs study.
It is critical of the UK's educational and skills base. 'Improvements are
required if the UK is to reduce the large discrepancy between its ratio of
skilled to unskilled workers compared with those of Germany and Japan,' it
says.
But it praises the Re-Start programme for the long-term unemployed and the
general approach to labour market deregulation which has made the UK labour
market 'one of the least regulated in Europe, if not the entire OECD area'.
The OECD researchers seem puzzled why this has not led to better results.
The report says: 'It may be that the positive effects of structural reform
take longer to bear fruit than originally assumed.'
The report is critical of continuing real-wage rigidity. 'Real wage growth
during the most recent cycle continued long after the recession had
started,' it says.
</TEXT>
