<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Profits up at Nuclear Electric
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nuclear Electric, the state-owned nuclear power generator, yesterday said
that some of its stations could, for the first time, produce electricity for
less than its selling price.
It said its five advanced gas-cooled reactors had cut generation costs to
2.6p per unit compared with the 2.7p which the company received, on average,
for its output. The company hailed this as 'a major breakthrough' which
reinforced the case for privatisation.
Mr John Collier, the company's chairman, said: 'The time has come for a
rethink of our status as a public-sector company.'
Yesterday's announcement, made as Mr Collier announced the company's results
for the year ending March 31, came only a month after the government
launched its review of the nuclear industry, one aim of which is to
determine whether Nuclear Electric should be privatised.
The results showed that the company made further strides in the direction of
cutting costs and raising its share of the electricity market in England and
Wales. Its profits amounted to Pounds 361m, up from Pounds 109m last year.
This included income of Pounds 1.2bn from the nuclear levy, which adds about
10 per cent to electricity bills. Without the levy Nuclear Electric would
have made an operating loss of Pounds 434m, although this was an improvement
on the previous year's loss of Pounds 616m. Nuclear Electric has set next
year as the target date for making a profit without the levy, which is due
to be phased out by 1998.
The company presented its accounts in a way which distinguishes its present
operations from those inherited from the Central Electricity Generating
Board. The first made a profit of Pounds 702m and the second a loss of
Pounds 341m, mainly because the older stations have large clean-up
liabilities which are not fully funded.
Nuclear Electric's income from electricity sales was up by 21 per cent to
Pounds 1.7bn, with most of the increase coming from advanced gas-cooled
reactors. Productivity measured by electricity produced per employee rose 27
per cent.
The older Magnox stations are still holding back the company. Their
production costs were 3.8p per unit, nearly 50 per cent higher than the
AGRs.
Nuclear Electric's share of the electricity market in England and Wales rose
from 21.6 per cent to 23.2 per cent. It expects this share to rise further
next year as the new Sizewell B station comes into operation. Nuclear
Electric is now the second-largest generator in England and Wales after
National Power.
Mr Bob Hawley, chief executive, said it was 'a year in which we clearly
demonstrated that we are fit to enter the private sector'. He said that
apart from keeping open the nuclear option, development of the nuclear power
industry would bring substantial environmental benefits because it produced
no atmospheric emissions.
</TEXT>
