<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / CBI chief hails broader family credit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's interest in extending family credit, the in-work benefit
for low-paid people, was both welcomed and criticised at the conference.
Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the Confederation of British Industry,
supported the idea - floated by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor - of
extending the benefit to single people.
Mr Davies said it was the most effective way of encouraging job creation by
keeping down the price of labour to the employer while ensuring that income
to the employee does not sink too low.
He said: 'The rapid growth in earnings dispersion is emerging as a more
serious social and economic problem than is yet appreciated by most
politicians.' Lord Lawson recently expressed the same view.
Mr Andrew Britton, director of the National Institute of Economic and Social
Research, expressed doubts about family credit. He said it required an
intrusive means test.
Mr Britton said: 'A relationship of dependency is unavoidable between the
recipients and the state as the donor. This may be right and proper as a
temporary relationship for individuals or households in times of particular
adversity, but it is not so appropriate as a permanent relationship between
the state and perhaps millions of skilled workers.'
He said that family credit could act as a disincentive to seeking promotion
or better paid work as the benefit was phased out as incomes rose, leaving
the individual no better off.
Mr John Monks, general secretary of the TUC, said the TUC was interested in
the idea of in-work pay supplements but warned that 'the government must
guard against subsidising employers' lousy pay and conditions, and taking
advantage of both their employees and the state'.
</TEXT>
