<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Building upturn 'to remain weak'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The construction recovery will remain weak because of a sluggish housing
market and lower public spending, say independent forecasters which
previously provided output estimates for the National Economic Development
Office, Andrew Taylor writes.
But figures published by the Department of the Environment yesterday showed
that housebuilding activity continued to increase during the first five
months of this year.
The department said builders started work on 7 per cent more homes during
the three months to the end of May compared with the corresponding period
last year.
More recently, builders and estate agents have reported that the pace of
sales recovery has faltered after increases in tax and fixed interest rate
mortgages.
According to Construction Forecasting and Research, total construction
output is likely to rise by 1 per cent this year, by a further 2 per cent
next year and 2.5 per cent in 1996.
This follows three consecutive years of decline in which the value of
construction output at constant 1990 prices fell by 12 per cent.
Mrs Jacquie Cannon, CFR director, said: 'While there are many positive
indications, the fragile state of the housing recovery together with the
problem of government finance does dampen expectations.'
Infrastructure output, which had risen by two-fifths between 1990 and last
year helped by the construction of the Channel tunnel, is forecast to fall 9
per cent this year and a further 5.5 per cent next year.
Private-sector housing output, which rose 9.5 per cent last year, is
forecast to rise 5.5 per cent this year and 7 per cent next year.
JFC Construction Forecasts 1994/5/6. Princes House, 39 Kingsway, WC2B 6TP.
Pounds 75.
