<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / The Rail Dispute: Pay curb halted 5.7% deal - June offer
would have avoided conflict
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A deal over signalmen's pay could have been reached early last month between
Railtrack and the RMT transport union, written evidence to the Commons
employment committee showed yesterday.
The deal would have avoided the industrial conflict which includes a further
24-hour strike today. But it was torpedoed by government intervention on the
grounds that the deal would have breached its policy on pay in the public
sector.
The evidence emerged at a public session of the committee at which MPs
questioned Mr Robert Horton, Railtrack chairman, and Mr Jimmy Knapp, general
secretary of the union. It was disclosed at the session that Mr Horton had
been in regular contact with Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary,
since the conflict began early last month.
Railtrack, a company wholly owned by the government, indicates in its
written evidence to the MPs that it believed union negotiators were ready to
agree an interim settlement. It would have increased basic pay of signalmen
by 5.7 per cent in recognition for past efficiency improvements.
The company also discloses that the union was prepared to settle on terms
acceptable to Railtrack. Nineteen hours of 'exploratory' talks spread over
June 6-8 had brought both sides to the point of a deal.
The company says: 'During these talks the Railtrack team formed the view
that the RMT might accept an offer of an increase in basic rates in the
region of 5.7 per cent (rather than the 11 per cent now claimed) accompanied
by some productivity improvements to meet their interim claim and enable
negotiations on the main restructuring proposals to proceed.'
The Railtrack position is confirmed by the RMT's written evidence to the
committee. This states that the company 'offered a 5.7 per cent increase in
basic rates of pay with conditions attached in recognition of productivity
and lost differentials'.
The RMT adds: 'Railtrack indicated they would put this proposal to us
formally on June 9 but this never materialised and under pressure from the
government, Railtrack withdrew it on 13 June.'
In its evidence Railtrack adds that 'the company's negotiating team reported
back on June 9 on the exploratory talks held over the previous three days
and the board discussed various options to resolve the dispute in the light
of these talks'.
That board meeting adjourned without a decision and then reconvened on the
following Monday. By the time the directors met again the line had changed -
because of intervention by the Department of Transport.
</TEXT>
