<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / The Rail Dispute: Horton and Knapp to 'chat' - Railtrack
chief to meet minister again
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Railtrack chairman Mr Bob Horton and Mr Jimmy Knapp, the RMT transport
union's general secretary, will meet soon about the increasingly bitter
signalling staff dispute.
This emerged yesterday when the two men appeared before the Commons
employment committee. After much pressure from Mr Greville Janner, the
committee's Labour chairman, Mr Horton agreed that he should have what Mr
Janner called a 'little chat' with Mr Knapp.
Mr Knapp was quick to accept a meeting. 'Yes, of course. I would be a fool
not to say so,' he told Mr Janner.
Mr Janner made clear at the start of the hearings that he understood that
neither side would want to prejudice a return to negotiations to try to
settle the conflict.
At one moment a Conservative member of the committee had to restrain an
increasingly irate Mr Janner who seemed particularly incensed to discover
that Mr Horton has been in regular contact with Mr John MacGregor, the
transport secretary, since the conflict began early last month.
The Railtrack chairman said he had seen Mr MacGregor 'three or four times'
and after consulting his diary informed Mr Janner his next session with the
transport secretary would be tomorrow.
The Railtrack team caused exasperation when they were unable to tell the MPs
what the average earnings of signal workers were.
Mr David Armstrong, the company's industrial relations director, ploughed
hurriedly through his file of documents in search of the vital statistics in
an increasingly frantic manner. Mr Janner suggested in headmasterly style
that perhaps he should leave the room to find the figure. Mr Armstrong
eventually revealed the figure to be Pounds 16,650 a year for a 50.1 hour
working week.
Mr Horton was in conciliatory mood. He said he did not regard the signal
staff as Luddites - 'the last word I would use to describe them'. He talked
warmly of a 'beneficial cycle' that would ensure the men high earnings in
return for productivity improvements.
Committee members expressed surprise at what they saw as the signalling
staff's poor levels of pay for long hours of work. Mr Knapp made it clear
that his members had 'strong feelings' about their pay grievances.
Mr John Major said yesterday that he was 'pretty fed up' with the rail
strikes. He said during a visit to Edinburgh that millions of people had
accepted low wage rises in the past two years. 'I don't think they would
think it right for Railtrack to concede an 11 per cent rise to the
signallers without any productivity improvements.'
</TEXT>
