<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / The Rail Dispute: Variety of views from the Railway Tavern -
Peter Marsh on a propaganda war which the signal workers are winning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As the rail dispute enters a new phase victory in the propaganda battle over
who is to blame is inching towards the signal workers' union.
Mr Bob Worcester, chairman of the MORI opinion poll company, said: 'The days
when strikes are automatically blamed on the trade unions are long gone. The
public perception is that the government and Railtrack have not handled well
their side of the dispute.'
This view is backed by an analysis of leading articles in national
newspapers since the strikes started.
Of 30 editorials in London-based daily papers, only six have singled out the
RMT union for blame, with 10 neutral and 14 apportioning most responsibility
either to the government or Railtrack.
In a highly unscientific poll by the Financial Times of the managers of 15
pubs around Britain, all called the Railway Tavern, only five said the union
was unambiguously to blame. Five put the responsibility on the other side
and five said they did not have a view either way.
Ms June Charles, landlady of the Railway Tavern in Mile End, east London,
accused the government of 'mismanaging' the dispute. Mr Sid Hogarth of the
Railway Tavern in Langley Mill, Derbyshire, said: 'The government has been
trying to prove it's the boss. If it hadn't intervened, the dispute would be
over.'
Mr Michael Burrell, managing director of Westminster Strategy, a lobbying
group, said: 'So far surprisingly little blame has come the way of the
union. A lot of people seem to think Railtrack has been a bit incompetent.'
According to Mr Greg Parston, director of the Office of Public Management, a
consultancy specialising in public-sector issues, the union's 'brilliant'
handling of the dispute had helped to build up public support.
Mr Parston also believes the tactic of one strike a week underlines the
importance of the dispute and keeps it in the public eye, while reducing the
chances of a backlash against the union by directly affecting only
relatively few people.
The degree of sympathy for the rail union in the FT poll of pubs was skewed
by region and type of customers. Publicans in the commuter belt of
south-east England, in particular, were more likely to blame the rail union.
Ms Debbie Spiers, landlady of the Railway Tavern in Staplehurst, Kent, said
her views were influenced by her customers, many of whom had been greatly
inconvenienced by the signal workers.
Mr Peter Kelly of the Railway Tavern in Andover, Hampshire, said: 'The
government has my support. Anyone who goes on strike should be sacked.'
</TEXT>
