<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Fading breed takes on 'grain barons': Small farmers are
seeking a bigger share of EU funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Thompson works an 80-hour week on his dairy and sheep farm on the
North Yorkshire Moors near Whitby. The holding is not big enough to make it
worth employing another pair of hands, and the 56-year old farmer is fed up
with the hard graft - he is considering giving up his cows and developing a
bed-and-breakfast business.
The long hours and poor income for Britain's 150,000 small farmers make them
a fading breed - 2,000 a year are leaving the business or taking part-time
jobs.
Today a group of small farmers will visit Westminster to press Mrs Gillian
Shephard, agriculture minister, to agree to changes in the Common
Agricultural Policy that would favour small producers.
Mr James Mulford, chairman of the Small Farmers Association, says: 'The
public agrees to support agriculture because they think the money is going
to small farmers like us. But 80 per cent of CAP spending goes to 20 per
cent of the biggest farmers: it's wicked.'
Mr Mulford does not want any additional cash, he wants CAP funds spread more
evenly by setting a cut-off point after which large holdings would fail to
qualify for aid. This would stop hundreds of thousands of pounds in
subsidies going to the 'grain barons'.
'These subsidies are just pure profit to some of my larger neighbours, but
every pound of aid I get goes to pay for food for my family,' says Mr
Mulford, who farms 200 acres in Suffolk.
If Mr Mulford's ideas were adopted there would be more funding to spread
among the whole farming population, with a greater proportion going to
smaller producers.
A small farmer typically has fewer than 200 acres and 80 per cent of family
income is generated on the farm. Under this definition almost half of
Britain's farmers can be termed small, but Mr Mulford argues that their
voices are never heard.
Smaller producers also say they are caught in a vicious circle - if large
farmers are enjoying a good year, as at present, their desire to expand
pushes up land prices and the cost of agrochemicals is increased, making it
harder for small farmers to compete.
Many large farmers hope to buy up their smaller neighbours in an effort to
cut costs and compete with lower-cost operators overseas when the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade deal comes into force next year.
Mr Thompson's farm could well be swallowed by a bigger landowner. It will
not support a full-time living when he retires, as on 30 of his 80 acres he
has only a life tenancy which cannot be passed on. But the bed-and-breakfast
business is also uncertain as fewer people choose to spend their main
holiday in Britain.
Mr Mulford says diversification by farmers has not been a big success - he
believes only two in every 10 projects prove successful. Farmers closest to
towns gain most by diversifying as there is a ready market for them, he
says, but this does not help those in more remote areas.
'There is increasing pressure on us to diversify, but if you're a small
farmer you are working flat out anyway and have no time to devote to a new
business,' he says.
Mr Mulford is hoping to convince Mrs Shephard to take notice of the
interests of the small producers. 'The large producers dictate the
agricultural debate in the UK and also in the European Union, but a small
mixed farm is what the public think of as a traditional holding and they
want to keep it that way,' he says.
Commodities, Page 34
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9641 Regulation of Agricultural Marketing.
    P01   Agricultural Production-Crops.
    P02   Agricultural Production-Livestock.
</IN>
