<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Cabinet reshuffle may save hospitals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday faced growing pressure to slow down its shake-up of
London hospitals amid signs of concern in 10 Downing Street about the public
backlash.
Ministers suggested last night that the impending Cabinet reshuffle could
provide the opportunity for a rethink of proposals in the Tomlinson report
to slim down radically the capital's hospitals.
Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, is widely expected to move to
a new department in a reshuffle which could come as soon as next Monday.
Her successor would be in a much stronger position to announce a review of
the planned hospital closures and mergers.
Mr John Major is said to be particularly concerned about the decision to
close in-patient services at Guy's hospital, one of the most advanced
research and teaching units in Britain.
Sir Philip Harris, a substantial benefactor to the hospital and a deputy
treasurer at Conservative Central Office, is among a number of influential
figures lobbying the prime minister to change Mrs Bottomley's decision.
An all-party group of MPs is leading a campaign to prevent the effective
closure of Guy's as part of its merger with St Thomas'. The merger is still
the subject of public consultation and opponents of the plan have threatened
a legal challenge.
Downing Street also appears uncertain of the financial calculations in the
original plan to close a number a leading teaching hospitals and cut the
number of beds in London by up to 2,500.
The British Medical Association yesterday angrily condemned the closure
plans. It voted unanimously at its annual conference for a reappraisal of
the 'disastrous' recommendations in the Tomlinson report.
</TEXT>
