<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Church plans housing scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than 300 chapels are expected to be demolished and replaced by social
housing in a scheme by the Presbyterian Church of Wales to take account of
falling congregations.
The church has 977 chapels, mostly Victorian, and a membership of less than
56,000, with some congregations as small as 12.
The Rev Daffyd Owen, the church's general secretary, said yesterday:
'Membership has been in steady decline since the end of the first world war.
Most of Wales has a huge overcapacity of church buildings - in many rural
areas the capacity is more than the total adult population.
'We think this is a positive reaction to the decline. A message has been
coming through that the church has not been sufficiently concerned about the
community at large and not using its resources in line with the gospel
message.'
The cost of repair and restoration of all the chapels has been estimated at
Pounds 35m. Mr Owen said: 'Even if we had the money, it would be ridiculous
to spend in that way.'
The sites will be valued and sold to Aelwyd (Hearthside) Housing
Association, set up three years ago by the church in conjunction with the
United Reformed Church and Baptists. The association will develop the sites
for those in housing need. The church intends to use part of the income from
the land sales to subsidise rents. Decisions on closures, which are expected
to be phased over 10 years, will be subject to final approval by the
church's general assembly. Worshippers would attend other nonconformist
services.
Mr Owen acknowledged that there was a great deal of opposition. He said:
'There is a very close emotional attachment between church members and their
buildings. It needs a sea change in our thinking and attitudes which I think
is vitally important.'
</TEXT>
