<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Plugs ruling is setback for two-pin campaign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The campaign to abandon the UK's three-pin plug and socket system in favour
of a proposed two-pin 'plug for Europe' received a blow last night after the
Department of Trade and Industry announced new regulations for domestic
appliances.
The controversial regulations, first proposed in January 1992, will require
most domestic appliances made in or imported into the UK to be supplied with
a correctly fused 13-amp plug from February 1 next year.
Supporters of harmonisation have been fighting the proposals because they
believe that they will lock the UK into the three-pin, 13-amp ring-main
system for years to come.
Mr Simon Hossack, a leading campaigner for the harmonised European system,
said: 'This is a triumph of politics over common sense.' The regulations
were a barrier to trade and would impede progress of a vital single market
goal, he said.
Mr Hossack added: 'Whatever plug is fitted to appliances will effectively
dictate the plug and socket system that the country uses. There would be no
incentive for the consumer to fit the new harmonised system when rewiring if
he had to cut off the plug supplied with the appliance.'
The new regulations are strongly supported by the UK plug and socket
industry and the Royal Society for the Prevention of Accidents on safety
grounds.
In a parliamentary written answer yesterday Lord Strathclyde, consumer
affairs minister, said: 'Fatalities and injuries occur each year because of
incorrectly fitted electric plugs. These regulations represent an important
step forward in consumer safety for the British public.'
</TEXT>
