<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Race body accused of bias
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A complaints officer with the Commission for Racial Equality yesterday
accused her employers of discrimination.
Miss Ila Dhorajiwala, who is of Indian origin, said she was overlooked by
the commission for a job which went to a white candidate.
She was desperate to move into personnel and had told her bosses she wanted
a transfer. She said she was stunned when she saw a vacancy in the
commission's human resources management department advertised in a magazine.
She failed to secure the job.
She told an industrial tribunal in Leeds: 'I have never been given any
reason why that happened. I think it is because of my race. I have seen
people of other races being transferred and given jobs and I cannot
understand why my transfer was not even considered.'
Miss Dhorajiwala, who joined the commission in 1987, said she had not come
across one coloured officer in human resources in the past four years.
The solicitor for the commission said Miss Dhorajiwala tried to get her job
in personnel through the back door.
Mr Paul Nicholls said she did not apply for the job, but asked for a
transfer from the complaints department to bypass the selection procedure.
'If you had put in an application you would have been shortlisted, but
instead you put in for a transfer,' he said.
The hearing was adjourned until tomorrow.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
