<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / World Cup '94: Italians hold off Nigeria for extra-time
victory
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Roberto Baggio and the Azzurri were about two minutes away from a date with
lions in the Coliseum of Rome in Foxboro, Massachusetts, yesterday, Jurek
Martin writes.
But the Italian superstar rescued his team with an 88th-minute equaliser and
then, in the 10th minute of extra time, converted the penalty that his own
lovely lobbed pass had helped create, giving Italy a 2-1 victory over
Nigeria in the World Cup second round.
If ever a game had two parts it was this. Nigeria took the lead in the 25th
minute in virtually their first attack. A corner from the right rebounded
off Maldini across the area to Amunike, who placed a sidefoot volley past
Marchegiani. Whereupon Nigeria sat on their lead and Italy attacked in
waves. But so stout was the Nigerian defence and so poor the Italian offence
that Rufai in goal had no serious save to make until Baggio beat him.
The goal followed a run from the right by Mussi, playing only his third
international, who gave Baggio a clear shot from a dozen yards inside
Rufai's right post. The winner came after Baggio lofted a dead ball to set
Benarrivo through in the area, where he was clattered down by Eguavoen. The
penalty went in off the right-hand post.
That a penalty was called at all was the fitting climax of an eccentric
refereeing day by Arturo Brizio of Mexico. He issued nine yellow cards,
tying a World Cup record, five to Italians, though the match was never
vicious. His worst error occurred in the 75th minute when he sent off Zola,
a second-half substitute, for what seemed the mildest of tackles.
But two minutes later he decided not to send off Maldini, who had brought
down Yekini with the sort of arm toss of which a sumo wrestler would have
been proud.
So Italy, as against Norway, won with 10 men. Even so, as the Nigerians
cranked up their attack, they left openings which both Baggios nearly
exploited. At the other end, Dino Baggio saved the day in extra time by
hooking a Yekini poke off the line.
Later, Yekini launched a bitter attack on Nigeria coach Clemens Westerhof,
saying the defeat was due to his tactical folly. He also criticised his
team-mates for not passing to him enough.
It was a match which salvaged Roberto Baggio's pre-tournament reputation -
though only just. After a bright beginning, he faded from the scene and
looked tense and unsmiling. The goal unleashed a talent that seemed withered
under pressure. Next come Spain on Saturday and their defence is far more
uncompromising than Nigeria's.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
