<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Man with new set of rules to learn
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Christo Liebenberg, South Africa's newly appointed finance minister, is a
respected member of the South African business community, report Philip
Gawith from London and Mark Suzman from Johannesburg.
Without any political background, and given his solid reputation as a
successful banker, he is seen as unlikely to diverge sig-nificantly from the
cautious fiscal policy framework established by Mr Keys. But he lacks Mr
Keys' charisma.
Mr Liebenberg, 60, was until February chief executive of Nedcor, South
Africa's fourth largest banking group.
Under his guidance, Nedcor had a good record of social involvement, and was
co-sponsor of the influential Nedcor-Old Mutual planning exercise a few
years ago. The resulting document set out policy proposals to help push
South Africa into growth and alleviate black poverty.
In politics, Mr Liebenberg will have to learn to play by a new set of rules
as he seeks to maintain fiscal stability in face of continued demands for
extra spending.
He will also have to try to earn the respect of his key cabinet colleagues,
especially Deputy Finance Minister Alec Erwin, and Minister Without
Portfolio Jay Naidoo, with whom he will have to work closely in implementing
the reconstruction programme, the centrepiece of the government's economic
policy.
</TEXT>
