<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Ex-central banker accused
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A former director of the Bank of Spain faces a Pta15m (Pounds 74,000) fine
following allegations of insider trading in connection with the removal late
last year by the Bank of Spain of the board of Banesto, the private banking
group. Mr Tomas Ramon Fernandez is alleged to have learned of the impending
move on Banesto in discussions at the Bank of Spain on December 23 and sold
Pta5m worth of personally held shares in Banesto the day before a central
bank board meeting on December 28 which he attended. That meeting decided to
intervene in the banking group. Mr Fernandez claims he sold his equity in
Banesto to avoid a conflict of interest at the subsequent board meeting to
decide on the intervention. He was sacked from the central bank's board in
February after the stock market regulators began inquiries into possible
insider trading.
</TEXT>
