<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 94 / Fresh hope in search for EU chief: Britain lists names of
'broadly acceptable' candidates for Commission presidency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The emergence of seven possible candidates for the presidency of the
European Commission has reinforced optimism in Mr John Major's government
that there will be an early end to the dispute over the successor to Mr
Jacques Delors.
British ministers indicated that the names on a draft list of contenders -
drawn up in Whitehall but representing the government's understanding of the
position of other European Union member states - are all broadly acceptable
to London. The names have been canvassed during intense consultations among
EU governments after the deadlock at the EU summit in Corfu last month.
It also became clear yesterday that Mr Major now appears willing to risk the
anger of Euro-sceptics on the Tory backbenches by nominating Mr Neil
Kinnock, the former Labour leader, as Britain's second commissioner in
Brussels from January.
Among the fresh contenders for the Commission presidency are Mr Uffe
Ellemann-Jensen, the former Danish foreign minister, and Mr Pedro Solbes,
the Spanish finance minister. But Mr Giuliano Amato, the former Italian
prime minister, apparently remains the choice in London.
British ministers acknowledged that the list, which also includes candidates
from the Netherlands, is by no means final. A strong contender from Belgium
might yet emerge within the next few days. Mr Peter Sutherland, Irish
director-general of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, could also
re-enter the race.
But comments by Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany yesterday that Spanish
prime minister Mr Felipe Gonzalez has ruled himself out of the race
strengthened the view in London that the successful candidate most probably
will be drawn from the names now circulating.
Mr Kohl, who as president of the EU council is preparing the ground for a
decision at or before the Brussels summit on July 15, signalled also that Mr
Delors is unlikely to extend his presidency.
Apart from Mr Ellemann-Jensen, Mr Solbes and Mr Amato, the other four being
mentioned in London are Mr Ruud Lubbers, the outgoing Dutch prime minister
who failed to muster enough votes at the Corfu summit; Mr Hans Van den
Broek, the Dutch commissioner in Brussels for external political affairs; Mr
Renato Ruggiero, at present Italy's candidate to head the World Trade
Organisation; and Mr Poul Schluter, the former Danish prime minister.
Britain is unwilling to give public support to any individual candidate for
fear of a backlash from other EU governments in the wake of Mr Major's
decision in Corfu to veto the candidacy of Mr Jean-Luc Dehaene.
But it is clear that Britain's first preference is Mr Amato and it would
also be happy with Mr Ellemann-Jensen or Mr Solbes. Mr Major is said to have
no 'overwhelming objection' to the other candidates.
It is understood that Mr Major will delay a final decision on whether to
propose that Mr Kinnock join Sir Leon Brittan at the Commission until after
the new president has been chosen.
But colleagues say the prime minister is ready to remove the bar he placed
on the former leader when Mr Kinnock was first suggested two years ago. If
that position is confirmed, the government is likely to press for Mr Kinnock
to be given the overseas development portfolio.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Passing a Major hurdle: seven man the UK would not veto
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
John Major
Ruud Lubbers                   Netherlands
Hans Van den Broek             Netherlands
Giuliano Amato                 Italy
Renato Ruggiero                Italy
Poul Schluter                  Denmark
Uffe Ellemann-Jensen           Denmark
Pedro Solbes                   Spain
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
