<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hopes of greater stability for the US dollar, together with renewed firmness
in European bond markets, brought an advance in the derivatives, although
volumes remained thin, writes Joel Kibazo.
The September futures contract on the FT-SE 100 opened at 2,952 and buying
from independent traders, also known as locals, steadily sent the contract
ahead.
The strength of bonds provided a useful lead to futures and the release of
UK economic data helped to boost trading further,
US markets, usually a factor in afternoon trading, were closed for the
Independence Day holiday, but September remained in positive territory for
most of the session and reached a peak of 2,988. It was at a premium to cash
for most of the day.
The contract finished at 2,987, up 38 from Friday's close and about 10
points above its fair value premium to cash which has fallen to 5 points on
this account. Volume was very thin, a mere 7,695 lots being dealt by the
close.
Turnover in the traded options was also poor, amounting to just 18,342
contracts. Only 4,156 lots were traded in the FT-SE 100 option and 3,550 in
the Euro FT-SE option. Lasmo, which recently escaped the clutches of
Enterprise Oil, was the busiest stock option with a total of 3,327 contracts
traded.
