<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / Markets Report: Dollar moves narrowly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Independence Day holiday in the US, and caution ahead of today's Federal
Open Market Committee (FOMC) meeting, ensured that the dollar yesterday
traded in a fairly narrow range, writes Philip Gawith.
The US currency finished little changed in London, at Y98.9 from Y98.705 on
Friday, and DM1.5965 from DM1.5946.
With the US markets closed, the currency market had effectively shut by
mid-afternoon in London, with one leading bank reporting that most of its
spot traders had taken off to watch the crucial Ireland-Holland match in the
World Cup.
Traders said investors, faced with a bewildering array of monetary policy
meetings this week, appeared to have taken to the sidelines. There is
increasing scepticism, however, about the likelihood of co-ordinated policy
action in support of the dollar from leading industrial nations.
In Europe, the Swedish krona and Italian lira recovered from their weakness
of last week. The pound had an uneventful day, the sterling index ending
steady at 79.6.
There was little fresh news for the market to chew on, save for comments
from President Clinton that 'we do not believe a country can devalue itself
into prosperity'.
Commenting on the dollar's recent weakness, Mr Clinton added that 'great
care should be taken before unusual actions are taken'. Some traders
interpreted this as diminishing the likelihood of concerted intervention.
Bolstering this impression were remarks from Mr Gert Haller, state secretary
in the German Finance Ministry, that the current dollar/D-Mark rate, of
about DM1.60, 'corresponds to the long term average'. He added: 'I have not
understood the excitement about the dollar in relation to European
currencies.'
While few analysts rule out the possibility of a monetary tightening from
the policy-making FOMC, most agree that this would be motivated by domestic
economic conditions, rather than the weakness of the US currency.
Similarly, analysts said any monetary easing from the Bundesbank council,
which meets on Thursday, would be tied to domestic factors.
Mr Peter Luxton, economist at Barclays in London, said if the FOMC
authorised a rise in rates, it was possible that Mr Alan Greenspan, Federal
Reserve chairman, would be given leeway to move only after he has seen
Friday's payroll figures, and the preliminary second-quarter GDP figure
later this month.
The Barclays economist said a 'do nothing' policy might be the best option,
and that an intervention strategy was very dangerous as it provided markets
with a target to aim at.
But Mr Paul Chertkow, head of global currency research at UBS, said he did
not believe finance ministers and their political leaders were ready to risk
a 'crisis of confidence' in international markets. He added that recent
dollar weakness had been a catalyst for financial market weakness, and
predicted that this causality will continue.
Mr Chertkow doubted whether G7 leaders will come up with a pre-emptive
strategy to defend the US currency, and expected more intervention as a
response to further dollar weakness. He said this is likely next week when
the market wakes up to discover that there is no strategy to defend the
dollar.
Chase Manhattan, in its weekly foreign exchange analysis, notes that
'although G7 intervention has seldom been effective at the first or second
attempt, it generally has been effective eventually'.
The bank makes two further points: there has so far been little intervention
from the G7, with past episodes seeing 10 or more episodes of intervention
before markets turned. Second, there has been more limited G7 success with
intervention on dollar/yen than on Dollars /D-Mark.
In Europe, attention focused again on the lira and krona. Against the
D-Mark, the lira finished in London at L990.6 from L994.7 and the krona at
SKr4.890 from SKr4.906.
The recovery in the krona was tied up with the Swedish bond auction, which
went off more successfully than expected. Analysts said there was evidence
that the weakness of the krona had enticed foreign investors to participate
in the bond auction.
Mr Chertkow said the recovery in the lira was perhaps linked to market
rumours that the government planned, later this week, to announce
significant cuts in public expenditure. This would help address market
concern about the size of Italy's budget deficit.
The general torpor infecting markets spread to interest rate futures, where
volumes were at a very low ebb. But the firmer tone in the bond markets
helped prices, with the December Eurosterling contract closing at 93.73,
from 93.71. Only 2,782 lots were traded.
The December Euromark contract saw 5,042 lots dealt and ended at 94.97 from
94.94.
In the money markets, German call money rates eased to 5.05/5.15 per cent.
In the UK, the Bank of England provided Pounds 915m liquidity to the market
after forecasting a Pounds 900m shortage. Overnight money traded between 3
1/2 and 5 per cent.
</TEXT>
