<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: London aluminium price touches
a 39-month high
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Aluminium touched Dollars 1,530 a tonne, a 39-month high, on the London
Metal Exchange yesterday as investment funds continued to make their
presence felt in the metal markets.
However, some profit-taking emerged and there was no support for prices from
the US, where markets were closed for Independence Day. As a result
aluminium for delivery in three months eased back to close at Dollars 1,519,
up Dollars 9.
Aluminium's fundamental situation was improving, said Mr Angus MacMillan,
research manager at Billiton-Enthoven Metals, 'but the market appears to
have run ahead of itself to some extent'. Cuts in western world daily output
had yet to translate into a sustained fall in the huge stocks overhanging
the market.
Mr MacMillan said that, if prices continued to strengthen, producers might
be tempted to restart capacity at present shut down. However, for the time
being Billiton was assuming this would not happen and it had revised its
aluminium price forecast for 1994 up from an average of 54 cents a pound
(Dollars 1,190 a tonne) to 60 cents.
