<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / UK Company News: Debt forgiveness helps put TBI Pounds 22.5m
in black
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TBI, the property investment and development company acquired by Markheath
in a reverse takeover in March, reported a pre-tax profit of Pounds 22.5m in
the year to March 31.
The results were distorted by the restructuring and debt forgiveness of
Pounds 27.2m. Markheath, which suffered in the commercial property downturn,
was heavily indebted to banks led by Midland and ANZ. It incurred a restated
loss of Pounds 68.8m in 1992-93.
In the reconstruction, Markheath acquired Thomas Bailey Investments, a
private property company in south Wales. The estimated net asset value at
completion of Thomas Bailey was about Pounds 7.2m, which was satisfied by
the issue of 37m new ordinary shares.
In addition, Markheath raised Pounds 24.1m via a share placing and open
offer. The company then changed its name to TBI and is now based in Cardiff
and London.
A one-off payment of Pounds 47m has been made to creditor banks and Pounds
27.2m written off. In addition to the new equity, about Pounds 25m of new
debt was raised with Barclays.
Mr Michael Rendle, chairman, said the balance sheet now indicated a company
of substance with net assets of Pounds 41.7m. 'Interest costs and overheads
are now more than covered by our rental income and we can address the future
with renewed confidence.' The property portfolio was valued at Pounds 96.5m
with annualised rental income of about Pounds 7m.
Earnings per share were 18.42p after debt forgiveness. Before, there were
losses of 3.88p (55.29p losses). No dividend is proposed but Mr Rendle said
the board intended to pay dividends at the earliest possible opportunity.
Mr Paul Guy, chief executive, said: 'There is a very good base to take the
company forward. We intend very much to be extremely active with regard to
acquisitions and disposals.'
One property, at Bridgend in south Wales, had recently been sold for Pounds
4.1m when it was in the books at Pounds 2.7m, he said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>TBI.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
