<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / UK Company News: Shareholders and creditors come to Camper's
rescue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CAROLINE SOUTHEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Camper and Nicholsons, the UK yacht builder, was saved from closure
yesterday.
Shareholders and creditors have agreed to a restructuring package.
Camper and Nicholsons had incurred trading losses of Pounds 1.66m over the
last three years.
The losses, which have been funded primarily by its Liberian-based parent
company Naiad Ship Finance Corporation, have been exacerbated by two bad
debts worth Pounds 720,000 which are subject to litigation.
Out of total liabilities of Pounds 4.3m, shareholders and associated
creditors were owed Pounds 3.4m and third party creditors Pounds 900,000.
The yacht-makers bankers are owed Pounds 250,000 but are not covered by the
deal.
The package was negotiated by the company's directors and corporate recovery
specialists from Coopers and Lybrand. The creditors agreed yesterday to the
voluntary arrangement drawn up by Coopers and Lybrand.
Under the voluntary arrangement, drawn up by Coopers and Lybrand, Naiad will
make a cash contribution of Pounds 250,000 to the creditors. This should
trigger a full recovery for the preferential creditors and 16p in the pound
for the unsecured creditors. This could rise to 60 per cent if the bad debts
are recovered and the company is sold within three years.
Camper and Nicholsons employs 115 people. It is no longer associated with
Camper and Nicholsons International, the yacht brokers.
Naiad, which has invested Pounds 8.5m in the company since gaining a 95 per
cent stake in 1982, will not reduce its shareholding under the deal but will
dispose of its shareholding if a buyer can be found.
</TEXT>
