<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / Councils plan on being Tour de France winners
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Southern England's local authorities were hoping last night that the balmy
weather would last a little longer and that Briton Chris Boardman would
continue to wear the yellow jersey as leader of the world's greatest cycle
race.
Kent, Hampshire and East Sussex councils, along with towns such as Dover,
Brighton and Portsmouth, are paying between Pounds 1m and Pounds 1.5m to
bring two stages of the Tour de France to Britain for the first time in 20
years, and hoping to recoup the cost through a visitor bonanza.
Although Boardman is given little chance of winning the 2,400- mile,
three-week race, which attracts an international television audience of
950m, it is hoped he will cling to the yellow jersey for the two British
stages tomorrow and Thursday.
The organisers, Societe du Tour de France, have taken the tour to countries
near France in recent years to broaden its interest. The last time it came
to Britain was in 1974 when a stage was run around Plymouth. It was not a
success.
This time, a stage will run 128 miles from Dover through Kent and East
Sussex and end in Marine Parade, Brighton. A second stage will see the 189
riders cover 113 miles in a Portsmouth to Portsmouth run through Hampshire.
To get the tour, towns where a stage begins or ends have to pay a fee to
Societe du Tour de France. Brighton has paid Pounds 90,000, for example,
plus Pounds 36,000 to Sport For Television, the British company which has
the UK television rights.
Portsmouth and Hampshire County Council are spending Pounds 500,000 on the
tour with a standard Pounds 90,000 going to Societe du Tour de France. The
rest is for signposting, promotion, road closures, policing and other
incidentals. East Sussex County Council has budgeted Pounds 100,000,
including Pounds 78,000 for road closures and special cycle tracks in places
such as Ditchling Beacon.
But the 'investment' as Mr David Knight, project manager in Portsmouth has
called it, could reap substantial returns.
Mr Graham Tubb at East Sussex Council says: 'We are being cautious and only
estimating 200,000 visitors. Others are talking about 500,000 in East Sussex
alone and possibly 1m visitors overall. You only need half a million
visitors spending five pounds each and you have more than covered your
costs.'
Ms Deborah Grubb, the head of arts and leisure at Brighton district council,
says: 'We have had to pay Pounds 150,000 to get the tour and we consider it
a snip. We will get hundreds of thousands of visitors. If they spend Pounds
20 each, we will make millions.'
Chris Boardman picture, Page 11
</TEXT>
