<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / Building suppliers provide evidence of recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT and ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fresh signs that the recovery is spreading across the UK economy emerged
yesterday, after building suppliers said an improvement in the housing
market had created a surge in the sales of construction materials this
spring.
Meanwhile, official figures also showed that retail spending remains
relatively buoyant in spite of April's tax increases - although hints have
emerged that consumers may be becoming more cautious in the way they use
credit cards.
Shares of building material suppliers rose nearly 3 per cent on the London
Stock Exchange yesterday after a 9.05 per cent rise in merchants' sales
during the three months to the end of May, compared with the corresponding
period last year.
The jump was led by a big increase in sales to housebuilders, reflecting the
improvement in the housing market earlier this year, according to the
Builders Merchants Federation which published the figures.
Mr Peter Gill, federation director, said sales had risen by 7.9 per cent
over the previous three months, the highest annual increase since 1987.
However, he warned: 'Reports from building societies, and some house
builders that the pace of the housing recovery is faltering are worrying.'
In another sign of economic pick-up, the Central Statistical Office said
consumers spent a record Pounds 3.06bn on credit cards in May, pushing the
total level of new consumer borrowing to near record levels of Pounds
5.16bn.
The level of credit card repayment, however, was also sharply higher, as
more consumers sought to settle their credit card debts. Net lending fell
sharply during the month to Pounds 203m, down from Pounds 412m in April.
This fall disappointed the City, which had expected a figure of about Pounds
350m. But the Treasury pointed out that the underlying trend remained
upwards, with net lending in the three months to May higher than in the
three months to February.
Any disappointment was also offset by a strong June figure for M0 - the
narrowest measure of money supply, chiefly notes and coins. This showed it
growing by 6.8 per cent last month compared with the previous June.
Some analysts suggested the figure indicated that June's retail sales data
would be strong. The Treasury pointed out, however, that the recent growth
in M0 also reflected the fact that lower interest rates were encouraging
consumers to hold more cash.
Housing market, credit card and M0 reports, Page 12
London stocks, Page 44
See Lex
</TEXT>
