<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / People: Clark's chemistry for overseas development
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Commonwealth Development Corporation, the UK's overseas development
finance institution, is getting a new director of managed business, Bob
Clark, 56, (right) who is retiring at the end of June from his post with
ICI, where he was chief executive of ICI Explosives. He is replacing Colin
Gatt, 59, who is retiring after 23 years with the CDC.
Part of the Overseas Development Administration (ODA), the CDC engages in
all sorts of project financing, ranging from Pounds 7.9m for an orange juice
plant in northern Costa Rica, announced earlier this month, to a seed farm
in Malawi.
A year ago, the CDC was given UK government approval to start operating in
Vietnam. The CDC is now looking to open an office in South Africa later this
year; it is likely to be the conduit for some Pounds 40m of funding to the
newly-democratised South Africa over the next three years.
The CDC has been operating for 46 years, initially as the Colonial
Development Corporation but in 1963 adopting 'Commonwealth' in place of
'Colonial'. It is now involved in some 240 projects in more than 50
different countries. Most of the projects are agriculturally-oriented;
investments exceed Pounds 1.6bn, with 85 per cent of the projects now in the
private sector.
The CDC has an enviable managerial record, for a government-backed
institution; it employs fewer than 500 staff to run its worldwide projects,
with annual running costs well below many other international financial
institutions. Britain's Mergers and Monopolies Commission gave the CDC high
marks in June 1992, for, among other things, its cost controls and cash
management. Cash-generative from its own past investments, it is currently
able to invest some Pounds 200m annually in new projects; it does not any
longer have 'fresh funds' from the government.
As director of managed business, Clark will be responsible for administering
those operations - some 30 of the largest - in which the CDC takes a
managerial role, by having a seat on the board as well as investing funds.
</TEXT>
