<DOCNO>FT943-16378</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EGEERACQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940705
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / The Full Employment Debate: Hunt for broader role sparks
dissent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Today's conference is not just a debate about unemployment. It is also an
important moment in the politics of the Trades Union Congress, David
Goodhart writes.
The idea for the conference - and the plan to invite business leaders and a
cabinet minister - was floated when Mr John Monks took over as TUC general
secretary last year.
It appeared then to be part of a widely supported plan for the TUC to reach
across the political spectrum to promote social partnership at work. But a
demonstration outside Congress House, and the absence of several senior
trade union leaders from the conference, shows that the TUC's attempt to
establish a more pluralistic trade unionism is facing teething trouble.
The plan to streamline the TUC's internal organisation has been implemented
 -at the price of some turmoil. But the invitation to Mr David Hunt, the
employment secretary, to the conference has been the last straw for many
unions.
The disapproval of a left-led union such as the TGWU general union may not
be that surprising, nor an alternative event at Conway Hall organised by the
Camden Trades Council. Leftwing trade unionists will, in any case, find
little to cheer in the cautious background papers at the official
conference. There are no instant plans for full employment and there is a
great deal of orthodox economics.
But even the GMB general union has objected to the invitation to Mr Hunt,
and Mr John Edmonds, its moderate general secretary, has other business
today. Unison, the public-service union, has also expressed its disapproval.
This may be no more than an irritation to Mr Monks. After all, Mr Howard
Davies, director-general of the Confederation of British Industry, spoke at
the 1992 TUC congress and Mr Stephen Dorrell, the financial secretary to the
Treasury, appeared at a TUC conference earlier this year.
But it does appear to show that some of the big Labour-affiliated unions do
not acknowledge that their enthusiasm for Continental-style social
partnership requires a less partisan attitude.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8631 Labor Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>ECON  Employment &amp; unemployment.
</TP>
