<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / The Full Employment Debate: 'Glib and irresponsible talk'
leads the debate on cause and effect - David Goodhart weighs the
contributors' arguments on the reasons for and costs of unemployment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Michael Perry, joint chairman of Unilever, recently said that 'glib talk
about full employment is alarmingly irresponsible'.
Most of the contributors to the TUC debate are 'irresponsible' in that they
believe full employment is possible, albeit hard to achieve.
Most of the writers who address the causes of unemployment point to the
economic 'shocks' of the 1970s and early 1980s - notably the sharp rises in
oil prices - as well as the strains caused by structural change which have
led to job losses in traditional industries and a reduction in demand for
unskilled workers.
Some papers, such as that by Mr Chris Freeman of Sussex University, stress
the effect of information technology, while that by Mr Richard Freeman of
Harvard University examines competition from low-cost countries.
Mr Freeman concludes that globalisation has had an impact on some unskilled
workers - but not as great as some people believe.
Ms Christine Greenhalgh and Ms Mary Gregory from, respectively, St Peter's
and St Hilda's colleges, Oxford, emphasise the loss of industrial capacity
and skills which creates a large group of long-term unemployed people who
are not re-absorbed into the jobs market even during periods of recovery.
Mr Andrew Britton of the National Institute for Economic and Social Research
says that full employment in the 1950s and 1960s was not the result of the
government intervention to finance extra spending, nor flexibility in market
mechanisms which were considerably more rigid than today.
What characterised the period was a condition of persistently high, and at
times excess, demand. Mr Britton suggests that what prevented wages and
prices from rising faster was the continued regulation of credit, foreign
exchange and investment, but also 'responsibility and public spirit' as a
restraint on inflationary pressure.
On the costs of unemployment, Mr David Piachaud of the London School of
Economics finds that the number of people living in poverty as a result of
unemployment tripled between 1979 and 1991 to more than 2m.
According to census studies unemployment raises the chance that a man will
die in the next decade by one-third, and by 50 per cent for those in middle
age. Mr Piachaud also finds a clear correlation between unemployment and
both crime and racism. Combining social security benefits and taxes forgone,
the cost of unemployment to the exchequer is put at Pounds 26bn per year, or
more than Pounds 9,000 per unemployed person. This is equivalent to
unemployment imposing a tax of 10 pence on basic rate income tax.
But none of the writers defines in any detail what full employment might be.
Several imply that, with fewer 'jobs for life' and a more competitive
economy, short-term unemployment might even rise. Mr Richard Layard of the
London School of Economics comes close to saying that full employment is the
absence of long-term unemployment - defined as people who have been
unemployed for more than one year.
Most agree that growth is not enough to create full employment, and nobody
supports protectionism or restrictions on the use of technology. Mr John
Philpott of the Employment Policy Institute says that 'supply-side problems
would seem to contribute more to unemployment in 1994 than was the case in
1944'. But that does not mean that either training or deregulation is the
answer.
Britain's labour market seems to reflect the worst of both the US and the
European systems, according to Mr Philpott. This means more relatively poor
people in work but also implies a high level of unemployment and welfare
dependency.
The most concrete proposals come from Mr Richard Layard and Mr Dennis Snower
of Birkbeck College, London University. Both favour big subsidies to
employers to take on the long-term unemployed. Ms Patricia Hewitt of the
Institute of Public Policy Research, and Mr Paul Ormerod, of the University
of Manchester, call for more innovative ways of sharing work around, but Mr
Philpott warns that changing the pattern of work will not in itself expand
its volume.
Several ideas for reforming the benefit system are floated, including a
lump-sum 'Back to Work' payment.
But Mr Britton concludes that society gave up full employment because the
cost in terms of other objectives was too high. He warns that returning to
it now will be costly - in terms of extra taxes or public expenditure
forgone - and will require a shift towards more social solidarity.
</TEXT>
<XX>
