<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / The Full Employment Debate: New consensus rethinks the
unthinkable - The TUC today hosts a conference on employment to mark the
50th anniversary of the wartime white paper on jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Full employment, or at least talking about it, is back in fashion.
Today's Trades Union Congress conference to mark the 50th anniversary of the
wartime coalition government's white paper on employment policy - with its
commitment to 'maintain a high and stable level of employment' - would have
been unthinkable a decade ago.
The attendance at Looking Forward To Full Employment of Mr David Hunt, the
employment secretary, is testimony to a new consensus about the urgency of
reducing unemployment which spreads far beyond the labour movement.
Mr John Philpott, director of the Employment Policy Institute think-tank,
contrasts the annual 1984 Mais lecture by the then Mr Nigel Lawson - now
Lord Lawson - which blamed unemployment on rigid labour markets and
relegated it to a 'residual' of economic policy-making - with the 1994 Mais
lecture by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor.
Mr Clarke not only said that unemployment must now be the 'main
preoccupation' of economic policymakers but added that he shared the white
paper's commitment to maintain a high and stable level of employment.
In 1984 registered unemployment was rising rapidly towards 3m, yet by the
time of this year's lecture the figure was still high - at 2.6m - but was
falling rapidly.
The apparent lesson of the 1987 and 1992 general elections, that mass
unemployment had ceased to be a central political issue - especially when
the trend was downward - no longer seems to apply. This may have something
to do with the demise of the jobs-for-life expectations of the middle
classes.
The agenda is, in any case, now open. A decade ago the papers for such a
conference would have been peppered with calls for a massive expansion in
demand and huge state-backed employment programmes.
The conference papers - mainly by centre-left academics but representing a
wide range of views - scarcely mention such things. Indeed, the introductory
paper by Mr John Philpott indicates that supply-side measures are the most
appropriate form of attack.
He says the conference should be seen as a contribution to the 'middle way'
 -between the deregulated US model with high job creation but meagre social
protection, and the regulated European model with low job creation but more
generous protection.
This is where the consensus usually breaks down - with the left believing
that the European model can still create jobs even with high costs, and the
right saying that there is a trade-off between protection and job creation.
But Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, now says there are
limits on how far Britain can go in reducing unemployment by allowing
incomes to fall sharply.
Similarly, the TUC papers propose a range of employment-friendly reforms to
the tax and benefit system while trying to take account of how radically the
pattern has changed since 1944.
But several TUC papers reject the idea of topping up low wages in favour of
a high minimum wage and a hefty dose of labour market re-regulation.
The tension between such policies and rapid private-sector job creation is
not discussed, however. Also no paper looks at job creation from an
employer's point of view, and there is little acknowledgement of the wider
dimensions of full employment.
</TEXT>
<XX>
