<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / Bargaining deal for Revenue staff: Non-union US computer
group to sign recognition agreement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Inland Revenue Staff Federation will tomorrow sign a formal union
recognition agreement with Electronic Data Services, the US computer
services company which has never dealt with unions in its home country.
The deal preserves the union's right to collective bargaining for the 1,900
staff of the Revenue's information technology office who are being switched
to EDS in Europe's largest information technology contract from public to
private sector extending over 10 years and worth more than Pounds 1bn.
After six months of negotiations IRSF members are to be offered a choice
between two employment contracts - an 'image contract' to replicate civil
service terms and conditions as closely as practicable, and the standard EDS
company contract.
Transferring staff will be able to switch to the standard contract if they
wish, and the two contracts will run in parallel for the foreseeable future.
New staff will be hired on the standard contract. The standard package
offers perks such as free medical and dental care and company cars for
certain grades. The image contract is the only one covered by collective
bargaining arrangements.
Mr Clough said that the most difficult hurdles in negotiating the image
contract were in making pension arrangements equal to those available in the
civil service, and in providing a formal appeals procedure.
The company, which has a number of pension schemes in place, has had to
construct a new one to reflect the civil service terms. Mr Roger McNulty,
the division's human resources director, said, however: 'If people decided
to transfer out of the union scheme into the standard scheme we wouldn't
want them transferring back again.'
Tupe - the transfer of undertakings protection of employment - legislation,
which protects the terms and conditions of public-sector employees whose
contracts are transferred to the private sector, meant that EDS had to make
a commitment to work with the union, which currently represents the majority
of the 1,900 staff affected.
Mr Peter Clough, managing director of EDS's Inland Revenue division, said:
'We came at it from the point of view that we needed to recognise the
unions.'
Mr Clive Brooke, general secretary of the IRSF, said: 'We believe that a
particular strength we can bring is the job security we are offering staff.
I think this is where unions will have an increasing role to play.'
Mr Clough said: 'Here is an opportunity where we can demonstrate how unions
can add value to an organisation.'
The next stage of what Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the
Treasury, has described as a 'strategic partnership' between EDS and the
Inland Revenue will be developing a working relationship between a public
body and a corporate operation. EDS is hoping that its methods will rub off
on the Revenue.
The company says it has an open-ended view of how long the side-by-side
contract arrangements will last.
</TEXT>
