<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / Credit card repayments bring fall in net lending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A big net repayment of credit-card debt resulted in a sharp fall in the
level of net lending in May, official figures showed yesterday.
The Central Statistical Office said net lending to consumers through finance
houses, bank Visa and Mastercard credit cards and non-mortgage building
society loans fell to a seasonally adjusted Pounds 203m in May.
That was sharply lower than Pounds 412m of net lending in April and below
market expectations of Pounds 350m.
Analysts pointed out yesterday, however, that the underlying message in the
three-monthly figures, which are considered a better guide to the trend than
the volatile monthly data, was that consumers were continuing to borrow in
spite of tax increases.
Net lending in the three months to May was Pounds 1.13bn compared with
Pounds 1.11bn in the three months to February.
Most of the fall in May's net lending figure came from increased credit card
repayment, the CSO's figures showed. Although consumers spent a record
Pounds 3.06bn of new credit on their cards in May, there was a net repayment
of Pounds 104m as consumers settled their credit card bills faster.
This compares with credit-card net lending figures of Pounds 98m in April
and Pounds 78m in March.
Lending through building society loans fell to Pounds 3m in May from Pounds
14m in April. However new credit advanced by building societies rose to a
record Pounds 218m. The CSO said this might reflect a greater level of
building society lending 'following the transfer of business from a bank to
a building society'.
The level of finance house lending - used for car and store credit deals -
remained relatively flat at Pounds 304m in May, from Pounds 300m in April.
This surprised some analysts, in light of the recent rise in car sales and
the relatively strong performance of the white goods sector in May.
New borrowing for vehicles fell to Pounds 858m, down from Pounds 871m in
April and Pounds 968m in March. New borrowing for the home improvements
sector rose to Pounds 67m in May, from Pounds 59m in April.
New borrowing on store goods rose to Pounds 238, from Pounds 214m in April.
</TEXT>
