<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / University year move may be rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Universities yesterday seemed likely to reject a plan to shift the beginning
of their academic year from October to January, John Authers writes.
The Universities and Colleges Admissions Service, which co-ordinates
applications to all higher-education colleges, said this would be necessary
to accommodate the vastly expanded number of applicants.
Students would not make applications until after their exam results were
known at the end of August, it suggested, while the practice of making
offers conditional on A-levels should be abandoned. Universities would then
be able to plan with certainty to ensure that they did not exceed government
targets, while potential students would be able to make more realistic
applications.
But vice-chancellors fear this would involve too much upheaval for a system
which is also planning to introduce a new degree structure.
Instead the Committee of Vice-Chancellors and Principals, which represents
university managers, said it was likely to campaign for exam results to be
released earlier. The year could then start in September, allowing
universities to run three 15-week semesters each year.
The committee said two-thirds of its members wanted the marking of public
exams to be accelerated. They thought this was plausible because marks for
the equivalent baccalaureat qualification in France are available six days
after the exams have been completed.
</TEXT>
