<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / MoD admits failure on cost controls: RAF refurbishment to be
probed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Ministry of Defence last night announced an independent investigation
into how almost Pounds 400,000 was spent on refurbishing the official
residence of Air Chief Marshal Sir Sandy Wilson.
Mr Jeremy Hanley, minister for the armed services, said the total cost of
Pounds 387,000 - Pounds 127,000 more than he indicated in March - implied a
failure of the govern-ment's financial control system.
In a reply to a question from Sir James Spicer, Dorset West, Mr Hanley said
the external investigation would 'recommend appropriate action to ensure
there is no repeat' of the spending which took place in the past two years.
A further Pounds 9,000 was spent on routine maintenance.
Mr David Clark, shadow defence secretary, said: 'There appears to be one
rule for the top brass, who get away with spending so much money on
themselves, and another for the rest of the forces, many of whom are
threatened with the sack.'
The results of the defence-cost study, which started after the November
Budget, is expected to lead to thousands of redundancies when it is
announced in the next few weeks.
The study is aimed at helping the ministry save about Pounds 1bn in its
annual spending from the 1996-97 financial year. Labour fears it will lead
to the loss of about 25,000 jobs.
The MoD said an apparent failure of its financial control system could not
be linked to the defence-cost study, which aimed at cutting costs without
affecting the forces' effectiveness.
Mr Clark said he feared a misuse of government funds in refurbishing
official residences of other senior military officers.
The government has set up a separate audit of expenditure on official
residences to ensure that there are no other breaches of its financial
control mechanisms.
</TEXT>
