<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / Swoop on BCCI leaves victims still in the dark: Depositors,
creditors and employees are waiting for redress three years on
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
On July 5 1991 customers, staff and passers-by watched with varying degrees
of horror and surprise as the doors of Bank of Credit and Commerce
International were closed in a sudden sweep by global regulators.
Three years later many hundreds of thousands of depositors, creditors and
employees of BCCI around the world are still awaiting some signs of redress
following one of the biggest bank frauds in the world - totalling more than
Dollars 12bn.
Many of the employees have been hit three ways. They have lost their jobs,
they have lost their salaries and they haved been under pressure to repay
their subsidised mortgages and other loans with the bank. The stigma
attached to BCCI has made it difficult for many to find other employment.
For UK-based sterling customers of the bank the depositors' protection
scheme provided compensation of three-quarters of their savings up to Pounds
15,000. Equivalent schemes have been triggered in some other countries.
Creditors, however, are likely to have to wait well into next year for any
payout from liquidators. Depending on a Dollars 1.8bn contribution under
negotiation with Abu Dhabi, the bank's majority shareholder, they may
receive a payout of about 15p to 20p.
Further payments will depend on continued attempts to trace assets and to
settle litigation launched by the liquidators against bank regulators,
auditors, directors and related parties involved in transactions with BCCI.
The prediction remains an ultimate 30p to 40p in the pound.
The primary beneficiaries so far have been the professionals - several firms
of lawyers, consultants and notably the partners at Touche Ross, the
accountants, who have been liquidators to the bank.
For some of the main protagonists involved, criminal justice has been a
little swifter. Last month the authorities in Abu Dhabi, the majority
shareholder in the bank, sentenced 12 former executives to pay Dollars 9bn
in compensation and serve a total of 61 years in prison.
One of these, Mr Swaleh Naqvi, the chief executive, is now in the US where
he may be tried on a series of state and federal charges. Mr Agha Hasan
Abedi, BCCI's founder who was sentenced in his absence, continues to live in
Pakistan.
Meanwhile, a number of changes to regulation and banking supervision have
been made following the report in October 1992 by Lord Justice Bingham into
BCCI's supervision.
A new law in Britain has made it compulsory for the first time for auditors
to report suspicions of fraud to the regulators. Under previous rules they
were merely protected if they decided to do so.
Draft banking legislation proposed for the EU would give supervisors power
to refuse to authorise banks which are organised in a way that impedes
effective super-vision.
The Bank of England has set up an in-house legal unit and a special
investigations unit designed to help investigate matters.
It said yesterday: 'Undoubtedly there has been a change of emphasis. We have
become clearer on when we need to change gear from a trusting, supervisory
to a regulatory approach.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
