</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / Views sought on rolling settlement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pro-Share, the London Stock Exchange-backed group which promotes wider share
ownership, has launched a survey to assess the requirements of small
shareholders under a 'rolling settlement' share purchase system.
In particular, Pro-Share wants to find out how much direct contact
shareholders want to have with the companies they invest in if they are
forced into the use of so-called nominee companies.
Starting on July 18, the traditional two- to three-week settlement period
will end and shares will have to be paid for or delivered within 10 business
days of the bargain being struck.
The move to rolling settlement is expected to increase the use of nominee
companies which will hold customers' shares in the nominee's name, although
beneficially for the client. That means all communication the company
formerly had directly with the shareholder will be held instead with the
nominee company.
Pro-Share has helped to devise a proposed code of conduct for nominees which
would require that 'non-asset related' materials from the company is sent to
actual shareholders. These are materials such as annual reports which do not
suggest actions on 'matters affecting the value of the company'. But on
matters such as takeover bids, the code will not require nominees to
ascertain the preferences of actual owners before voting on their behalf.
</TEXT>
