<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / Retention of two-tier Staffs urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stoke-on-Trent and Newcastle-under-Lyme should come together to form a
single unitary authority but the rest of Staffordshire should retain two
tiers of local authority, the Local Government Commission for England
recommended yesterday.
The commission will seek the views of county residents in the next 11 weeks
before making its final recommendation to Mr John Gummer, the environment
secretary.
The commission's willingness to retain both the county council and district
councils, albeit over a reduced area, is at odds with the government's
preference for unitary authorities.
It follows a similar approach to that adopted in Kent, Hampshire and
Leicestershire, although the majority of commission recommendations so far
have been in favour of scrapping county councils.
All the district and borough councils in Staffordshire favoured the creation
of unitary authorities, although Lichfield and Tamworth wanted to merge. The
commission's preferred option is closest to the view of the county council,
which suggested a unitary authority for Stoke with a two-tier structure
elsewhere.
Union of Stoke and Newcastle, the north Staffordshire conurbation, would
create a community of 375,600 people. There is already 'a degree of
community interdependence', the commission concluded on the basis of a MORI
poll.
Newcastle Borough Council is against merger with Stoke, however, and
organised a petition that gained more than 11,500 signatures supporting
independence.
The commission said the financial implications of its preferred option were
'relatively minor'. Implementation would cost up to Pounds 10m and
administrative costs would be Pounds 4m a year less than current spending.
</TEXT>
