<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / MPs unite to urge child agency changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Conservative backbenchers joined opposition MPs in the Commons last night in
calling for the Child Support Agency to apply a less rigid formula when
setting the level of maintenance payments to be made by absentee fathers.
Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, ruled out significant
changes in the agency's operations before the next report by the Commons
social security committee due in October. He said improvements were already
evident after changes introduced by the agency in April.
Mr Richard Alexander, MP for Newark, Sir Donald Thompson, MP for Calder
Valley, and Mr John Horam, MP for Orpington, were among Tory backbenchers
who pressed for changes designed to ensure that the agency operated with
greater flexibility.
After describing the demands made by the agency on one of his constituents
with a net income of Pounds 127 a week, Mr Horam said: 'No wonder he came to
me and talked about suicide.'
Mr Frank Field, the Labour MP for Birkenhead, who is chairman of the
cross-party social security committee, said it had not yet reached a
position where it could say that the agency was working successfully and
achieving its objectives. He urged Tory MPs to impress on the government
that the 'jury was still out', and to be ready to support any changes
advocated by the committee.
Mr Donald Dewar, shadow social security secretary, said those dissatisfied
with the agency's decisions should have some possibility of securing
redress. While reaffirming Labour's backing for the principle that it was
the duty of parents to support their children, he said public support for
the agency was vanishing at an alarming rate.
Mr Lilley underlined his opposition to the introduction of an appeals system
which would result in a return to an 'open-ended' discretionary system.
A Labour motion calling for an urgent and fundamental review of the child
support agency was defeated by a government majority of 38 (311-273).
</TEXT>
