<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / Party electorate seeks some light in land of the bland:
Kevin Brown finds there is little difference between the manifestos of the
three leadership candidates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
So now we know what they stand for. Or do we?
The launch yesterday of Mr John Prescott's personal manifesto for the Labour
leadership completes a trio of election statements from the candidates to
succeed John Smith.
As expected Mr Prescott promised to establish a Commission for Full
Employment which would recommend a jobs programme to next year's party
conference. This body would be on the lines of the Social Justice Commission
set up by Mr Smith.
If there was a surprise, it lay in the reticence of the normally ebullient
shadow employment secretary. He was unwilling to set targets for achieving
the full employment policy he has set at the heart of his political
programme.
In that, however, he was following the lead given by Mr Tony Blair, the
modernising shadow home secretary, and Mrs Margaret Beckett, the party's
traditionalist interim leader who, with Mr Prescott, is also contesting the
deputy leadership.
None of the candidates has felt able to challenge the Labour convention that
only the party's annual conference may make policy.
As a result the manifestos have been bland to the point of banality, leaving
the 4.5m voters in Labour's three-part electoral college to scrutinise the
candidates' style and language to put some light between them.
There are differences, but they are not great. Mr Blair's manifesto is about
opportunity and security for individuals in a world where the global economy
has demonstrated the limits of government. Mrs Beckett's is about unity and
social cohesion. Mr Prescott offers a robust defence of collective action
and the state's role in employment creation.
With the race half over Mr Blair has a clear lead, assuming that the 154
Labour MPs who nominated him actually vote for him. Mr Blair is keenly aware
that he needs to maintain his image as the candidate best placed to win a
general election. That means avoiding mistakes between now and the
announcement of the result on July 21 - hence his infrequent public
appearances and his virtual absence from the cauldron of prime minister's
question time in the Commons.
Mr Prescott has not given up hope of capturing the leadership, although he
thinks he will have to come from behind to win. He believes that the media
has misjudged opinion in the constituency and trade union sectors of the
electoral college, which together control two-thirds of the votes.
There really is no evidence on this either way. There have been few polls
and although they have backed Mr Blair they have not distinguished eligible
voters from party supporters.
Friends say that Mr Prescott has been buoyed by the enthusiastic reception
he has received at campaign meetings around the country. Sceptics point to
Mr Michael Foot, the former Labour leader, who said much the same thing
during Labour's disastrous 1983 election campaign.
Mr Prescott's strategy is to win credit by bludgeoning the Conservatives and
by arguing for specific policy pledges to build credibility with the
electorate. He has a contempt for airy generalisations and freely uses such
words as socialism. But his willingness to offer specific commitments has
declined during the campaign. Full employment meant no more than 2.5 per
cent to 3 per cent of the workforce unemployed - now it is a matter for
debate.
Mrs Beckett stood for the job because she was annoyed, in part on feminist
grounds, that no-one took her seriously as a candidate after Mr Smith's
death, even though she was then his deputy. Her campaign has focused largely
on her competence as a former minister for schools in the Callaghan
government and as the party's deputy and interim leader.
The argument has some force. Mrs Beckett performed creditably in the
difficult weeks after Mr Smith's death. But there have been poor
performances in the Commons, notably after the prime minister's return from
the Corfu European summit.
Mrs Beckett started by shoring up her support on the left. Lately she has
sought broader support by presenting herself as the only candidate able to
unify the party's modernising and traditionalist factions. But critics say
her decision to run for both the leadership and deputy leadership was a
blunder which could lead to defeat in both contests.
She has appeared devious in refusing to say whether she really wants to be
deputy leader, and ungenerous in refusing to say whether she would serve in
the shadow cabinet under the rival candidates.
Mr Prescott, by contrast, has been keen to talk about the deputy's job,
which he has contested twice before. He has made the tactically astute
gesture of affirming that he would be honoured to serve in any post under
any leader.
Friends of all three candidates say they are confident that the campaign is
moving their way. But no-one knows how the union and constituency electors
will vote. The assured predictions that Mr Blair will be crowned leader
assume that they will follow the MPs' lead.
Friends of Mr Prescott and Mrs Beckett say this is a rash assumption. If
they are right, Mr Blair will not be the only one with egg on his face.
Joe Rogaly, Page 22
</TEXT>
