<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / Paris newspaper suspended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The conservative Le Quotidien, one of France's leading newspapers, announced
yesterday that it will suspend publication this week because of financial
troubles. The daily, edited by Philippe Tesson, will not appear from
tomorrow and the management said in a statement that a shareholders'
assembly on July 18 would decide whether to close it down or restart
publication in the autumn. The daily, which has a tabloid format but counts
among France's quality newspapers, was revamped recently to mark its 20th
anniversary. It was suspended briefly in 1979 but returned.
