<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JUL 94 / Cabinet plan to reform Whitehall pay bargaining: Top civil
servants to be put on personal contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Cabinet Office white paper due out this month will propose ending
centralised pay bargaining in Whitehall, giving individual departments
control over civil servants' pay and conditions.
In addition, about 2,000 top mandarins at grade five (assistant secretary
level) and above will be put on to personal contracts, with pay linked more
closely to their success in cutting civil service costs.
There is also likely to be a reduced emphasis on annual targets for
market-testing, the process by which civil servants compete against outside
bidders for their work.
The Treasury has become concerned over the cost of market-testing, while
many contractors are reluctant to bid because most contracts are won by
departments' own teams.
There will be increasing encouragement for privatisation, with departments
encouraged to get out of 'non-core' activities such as information
technology and buildings maintenance.
The Treasury wants to see much greater use of 'benchmarking', through which
managers compare costs with the most efficient comparable organisations and
restructure their own to achieve similar levels.
The white paper has been drawn up amid great secrecy by Mr William
Waldegrave, the public services minister, and approved by the prime minister
and a group of senior cabinet colleagues. Those include Mr Kenneth Clarke,
the chancellor, Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, and Mr Michael
Heseltine, trade and industry secretary.
It foresees a decline in civil service numbers from 554,000 last year to
below half a million over the next four years, the lowest level since the
second world war. When the Conservatives came to power in 1979, there were
732,000.
The main driver of change will be the freeze on running costs, which forces
departments to operate on declining real budgets until 1997. Ministers
believe permanent secretaries and agency chiefs will have to cut costs
radically to stay within targets.
To give them greater flexibility over pay, the biggest element in civil
service costs, departments will take over all personnel functions, including
pay bargaining.
Ministers, however, have rejected fixed-term contracts for senior civil
servants, because of fears that that would politicise Whitehall. Such
contracts have been advocated by civil service critics such as Sir Peter
Kemp, the former permanent secretary responsible for many of the
government's public-service reforms.
Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the Confederation of British Industry,
said last night that the CBI would welcome the end of national pay
bargaining in the civil service.
'It would be a natural consequence of the freeze on running costs,' he said.
'Without that sort of flexibility, the civil service will soon run up
against skill shortages and local recruitment difficulties.'
But Ms Elizabeth Symons, general secretary of the FDA top civil servants'
union, said her members would judge the white paper on three criteria: 'Will
it promote civil service effectiveness rather than the dogma of the
marketplace? Will it sustain ministerial accountability and the political
neutrality of the civil service? And will it make the machinery of
government more open to public scrutiny?'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
