<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUL 94 / Chinese premier aims at German trade deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Li Peng, the Chinese premier, arrived in Germany yesterday at the start
of a six-day visit likely to focus on boosting bilateral trade, Reuter
reports from Bonn.
Mr Li, travelling with more than 30 officials and businessmen, will hold
talks with Chancellor Helmut Kohl. He will also meet Mr Gunter Rexrodt,
economics minister, Mr Klaus Kinkel, foreign minister, Mr Theo Waigel,
finance minister, and German business leaders.
During the visit, the two sides are expected to sign accords on
co-ordinating German and Chinese efforts to develop China's railway network
and the transport and telecommunications sectors. Mr Li will also travel to
eastern Germany, including Berlin, and to Munich.
There has been little sign in Germany of the controversy which dogged Mr Li
in Austria, where Vice-Chancellor Erhard Busek refused to see him in protest
at China's human rights record, and demonstrations were banned. However,
German human rights groups have called several protests, including one in
Bonn today.
Some members of Mr Kohl's Christian Democratic party, including Mr Heiner
Geissler, a leading liberal, and Mr Horst Eylmann, chairman of the
parliamentary legal committee, yesterday urged Bonn not to let Mr Li forget
human rights.
They noted in a statement that Mr Li was widely seen as responsible for the
bloody suppression of pro-democracy protests on Beijing's Tiananmen Square
in 1989. 'The talks must not only be about economic co-operation; above all
there must be demands for human rights in China to be respected,' the
statement said.
But Mr Heinrich Weiss, chairman of the China section of the Federation of
German Industry's East Europe Committee, said human rights and trade should
not be linked.
'You can't use the one to force the other,' he said on German radio. He said
China's record would automatically improve if it was bound into the
international community through trade links.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
